\begin_layout Standard
Nuclei with unpaired protons or neutrons have nonzero nuclear spins.
 This leads to a nuclear magnetic moment, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}=\gamma(\hbar\mathbf{I})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the gyromagnetic ratio
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\gamma$"
description "nuclear gyromagnetic ratio"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}$
\end_inset

 the nuclear spin.
 (We will use the convention of unitless spin operators, hence the explicit
 factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

.) Nuclei like this interact with magnetic fields via the Zeeman interaction.
 The Zeeman Hamiltonian is
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this chapter we will cite references only when necessary, since the content
 here parallels most introductory textbooks.
 Sources which the author relied on for this content were Duer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duer2005"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Slichter 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Slichter1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Schmidt-Rohr & Spiess 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schmidt-Rohr1994"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and a useful report by Goldman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Goldman1992"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hbar\hat{H}_{Z}=-\boldsymbol{\mu}\cdot\mathbf{B}_{0}.
\]

\end_inset

The units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{Z}$
\end_inset

 are rad/s and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the main spectrometer field, which is taken to be in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 direction: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{0}=B_{0}\hat{z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\mathbf{B}_0$"
description "NMR/MRI main magnetic field"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Hence, the Zeeman Hamiltonian (in rad/s) is
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\hat{H}_Z$"
description "Zeeman Hamiltonian"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{H}_{Z} & =-\gamma B_{0}\hat{I}_{z}\label{eq:theory:Zeeman-hamiltonian}\\
 & =\omega_{0}\hat{I}_{z},\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=-\gamma B_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the Larmor frequency of precession.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\omega_0$"
description "Larmor frequency"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 This identification anticipates the connection to the classical theory
 of precession.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
