The relative weakness of the nuclear Zeeman effect dictates the experimental
 constraints and features of NMR and MRI.
 Without 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}\gtrsim0.1$
\end_inset

 T, performing NMR and MRI experiments is difficult.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
But not impossible.
 In fact, NMR and MRI has been performed in the Earth's magnetic field (
\emph on
eg.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

see references 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Halse2006,Michal2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 Although weak, the Earth's magnetic field is extremely homogeneous.
 However, Earth's Field NMR and MRI are of limited practical utility, and
 typically can't observe any nuclei except 
\begin_inset Formula $^{1}$
\end_inset

H.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For MRI, the range of nuclei which can be imaged in clinically reasonable
 times is limited to 
\begin_inset Formula $^{1}$
\end_inset

H and a few others (
\emph on
