\begin_layout Subsection
Precession and the rotating frame
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The classical picture of NMR is a straightforward way to introduce basic
 NMR dynamics and experiments.
 The equations of motion for a magnetization 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 in a field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d\mathbf{M}}{dt}=\mathbf{M}\times(\gamma\mathbf{B}),\label{eq:theory:dM/dt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which describes the precession of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 around 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 at a frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=-\gamma B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Excluding relaxation, this compact equation contains all the classical dynamics
 of NMR.
 It applies whether 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 and/or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 are constant or varying.
 Nonetheless, it isn't terribly straightforward to use in practice.
 One of the problems with Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theory:dM/dt"

\end_inset

 is that it describes the dynamics of precession in the laboratory frame.
 Most calculations in NMR are simplified by working in the rotating frame,
 a coordinate system which rotates around the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 axis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Slichter 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Slichter1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 has a nice derivation of how vectors are transformed between the lab and
 rotating frames.
 Consider an arbitrary vector function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}(t)=\sum_{i=x,y,z}F_{i}\hat{i}$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{i}$
\end_inset

 unit vectors are aligned with the lab frame.
 Now, assume that this coordinate frame rotates with an angular velocity
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the lab frame time rate of change for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{i}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\hat{i}}{dt}=\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\hat{i}.
\]

\end_inset

The time derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}(t)$
\end_inset

 in the lab frame is now more complicated, but gives a useful result:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left.\frac{d\mathbf{F}(t)}{dt}\right|_{lab} & = & \sum_{i=x,y,z}\left(\frac{dF_{i}}{dt}\hat{i}+F_{i}\frac{d\hat{i}}{dt}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{i=x,y,z}\frac{dF_{i}}{dt}\hat{i}+\sum_{i=x,y,z}F_{i}\frac{d\hat{i}}{dt}\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{i=x,y,z}\frac{dF_{i}}{dt}\hat{i}+\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\mathbf{F}(t)\nonumber \\
 & = & \left.\frac{d\mathbf{F}(t)}{dt}\right|_{rot}+\boldsymbol{\omega}\times\mathbf{F}(t),\label{eq:theory:dft/dt-slichter}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\frac{d\mathbf{F}(t)}{dt}\right|_{rot}$
\end_inset

 is the time rate of change in the rotating frame.
 If we apply this to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

, then from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theory:dM/dt"

\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left.\frac{d\mathbf{M}}{dt}\right|_{lab}= & \mathbf{M}\times(\gamma\mathbf{B})\\
= & \left.\frac{d\mathbf{M}}{dt}\right|_{rot}-\mathbf{M}\times\boldsymbol{\omega}\\
\Rightarrow\left.\frac{d\mathbf{M}}{dt}\right|_{rot}= & \mathbf{M}\times(\gamma\mathbf{B}+\boldsymbol{\omega}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

And so, in the rotating frame Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theory:dM/dt"

\end_inset

 still applies, provided that we replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{0}$
\end_inset

 with an effective field
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{B}_{\text{eff}}=\mathbf{B}+\frac{\boldsymbol{\omega}}{\gamma}.\label{eq:theory:Beff}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When only 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}$
\end_inset

 is present, by convention the precession axis is taken to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 direction we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
B_{\text{eff}} & =B_{0}+\frac{\omega}{\gamma}\label{eq:theory:Beff-general}\\
\Rightarrow\gamma B_{\text{eff}} & =\gamma B_{0}+\omega\nonumber \\
\omega_{\text{eff}} & =\omega_{0}-\omega.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\text{eff}}=-\gamma B_{\text{eff}}$
\end_inset

 is the effective precession frequency in the frame rotating at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\text{eff}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{\text{eff}}$
\end_inset

 are both zero: the effect of the the main spectrometer field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{0}$
\end_inset

 has been completely removed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
NMR uses a 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 field to manipulate the magnetization.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\mathbf{B}_1$"
description "NMR/MRI oscillating, transverse magnetic field applied with coils."
literal "true"

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 field is applied in the transverse plane and oscillates at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{B_{1}}(t)=B_{1}\cos(\omega t+\phi)\hat{x}+B_{1}\sin(\omega t+\phi)\hat{y},\label{eq:theory:B1-lab-frame}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is some arbitrary phase factor.
 We make no assumptions about 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

: it could be on or off resonance.
 It's easiest to analyze the problem in a frame rotating at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 The time derivative is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left.\frac{d\mathbf{B}_{1}(t)}{dt}\right|_{rot} & =\left.\frac{d\mathbf{B}_{1}(t)}{dt}\right|_{lab}-(\omega\hat{z})\times\mathbf{B}_{1}(t)\\
 & =B_{1}(\omega-\omega)\sin(\omega t+\phi)\hat{x}+B_{1}(\omega-\omega)\cos(\omega t+\phi)\hat{y},\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In this frame it appears as a constant magnetic field perpendicular to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

, around which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 rotates according to Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theory:dM/dt"

\end_inset

.
 This rotation around 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is called nutation.
 Combining this result for 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 with the result for 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theory:Beff-general"

\end_inset

, the total effective field in the frame rotating at the frequency of the
 rf pulse is
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\mathbf{B}_\\text{eff}$"
description "The total effective field in a rotating frame."
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{B}_{\text{eff}}=\left(B_{0}+\frac{\omega}{\gamma}\right)\hat{z}+B_{1}\hat{x},\label{eq:theory:effective-field-B}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we have chosen the phase of the rf pulse 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 is along 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

.
