\begin_layout Subsection
The Bloch equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before getting too far into the discussion of how rf pulses (the 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 field) affect the spins, the Bloch equations should be introduced.
 These phenomenological equations incorporate relaxation into the dynamics
 described by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theory:dM/dt"

\end_inset

.
 The Bloch equations are approximate and do not accurately describe the
 dynamics of NMR in all situations
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

---
\end_layout

\end_inset

only in systems of isolated spin-
\begin_inset Formula $\tfrac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 nuclei in low-viscosity solutions are they exact.
 Still, they provide an excellent framework for intuitive understanding.
 And, even where they aren't rigorously accurate, they can often be modified
 to model the situation anyway.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bloch equations in the lab frame are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\frac{dM_{z}}{dt} & =\frac{M_{0}-M_{z}}{T_{1}}+\gamma(\mathbf{M}\times\mathbf{B})_{z}\\
\frac{dM_{x,y}}{dt} & =\gamma(\mathbf{M}\times\mathbf{B})_{x,y}-\frac{M_{x,y}}{T_{2}}.
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:theory:bloch-lab}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the spin-lattice or longitudinal relaxation time, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the spin-spin or transverse relaxation time, and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}\le T_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a result of the spin-lattice coupling that returns the magnetization
 to thermal equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}_{0}=M_{0}\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 via
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{z}(t)=M_{0}\left(1-\left(1-\frac{M_{z}(0)}{M_{0}}\right)\exp\left(-\frac{t}{T_{1}}\right)\right).\label{eq:theory:T1-recovery-general}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

There can be no transverse components of magnetization in equilibrium: 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{y}$
\end_inset

 must decay.
 They do so exponentially with time constant 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 via
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{x,y}(t)=M_{x,y}(0)\exp\left(-\frac{t}{T_{2}}\right).\label{eq:theory:T2-decay}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Dephasing of the precessing spins causes 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 relaxation.
 In practice, we often refer to spin-lattice and spin-spin relaxation as
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 relaxation, even in cases where there is not a single, well-defined value
 for either.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$T_2$"
description "Transverse relaxation time / spin-spin relaxation time"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$T_1$"
description "Longitudinal relaxation time / spin-lattice relaxation time"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, consider the Bloch equations for a sample in an NMR spectrometer under
 the influence of rf pulses on resonance.
 In this situation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{lab}=\mathbf{B}_{0}+\mathbf{B}_{1}(t)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{1}(t)$
\end_inset

 is rotating in the transverse plane at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 (Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theory:B1-lab-frame"

\end_inset

).
 Following the last section, in the rotating frame this becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{rot}=B_{1}\hat{x}$
\end_inset

, where we have chosen the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis to be the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Correspondingly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}\times\mathbf{B}_{rot}=B_{1}(M_{z}\hat{y}-M_{y}\hat{z})$
\end_inset

, so the Bloch equations in the rotating frame are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\frac{dM_{z}}{dt} & =\frac{M_{0}-M_{z}}{T_{1}}-\omega_{1}M_{y}\\
\frac{dM_{y}}{dt} & =\omega_{1}M_{z}-\frac{M_{y}}{T_{2}}\\
\frac{dM_{x}}{dt} & =0.
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:theory:bloch-rot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

