\begin_layout Standard
In thermal equilibrium, the sample has a magnetization 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}_{0}=M_{0}\hat{z}$
\end_inset

.
 In a simple NMR experiment, a 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 pulse is applied to tilt 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 away from the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-axis.
 Experimentally, this is achieved by applying an oscillating voltage 
\begin_inset Formula $V(t)$
\end_inset

 across the coil resonance circuit,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(t)\sim\exp(-i(\omega t+\phi))
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is phase under the experimenter's control.
 This causes an oscillating, linearly-polarized 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 field,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{B}_{1}(t)=2B_{1}\cos(\omega t+\phi')\hat{x},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $2B_{1}$
\end_inset

 is an amplitude under the control of the experimenter.
 Regarding the phase factors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi'$
\end_inset

 vary only by an additive constant for a given sample and experimental set-up.
 Therefore, the relative phases of multiple 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 pulses (either in the same experiment or in repeated experiments) can be
 carefully controlled.
 In other words, the rf pulses used in NMR and MRI pulse sequences are coherent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The oscillating 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 field along the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis may be mathematically decomposed into two counter-rotating fields
 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 plane:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{B}_{1}(t) & =2B_{1}\cos(\omega t+\phi')\hat{x}\nonumber \\
 & =B_{1}\left(\cos(\omega t+\phi')\hat{x}+\sin(\omega t+\phi')\hat{y}\right)+B_{1}\left(\cos(\omega t+\phi')\hat{x}-\sin(\omega t+\phi')\hat{y}\right).\label{eq:theory:B1-counter-rotating}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Under most circumstances, the field rotating opposite to the precession
 direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 has negligible effect on the spins' dynamics, and can be safely ignored
 in the analysis of most experiments.
 As such, with a linearly-polarized 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 field, half of the rf power is wasted.
 In NMR, this rarely poses a large enough problem to address, since doing
 so requires non-standard coil designs and resonance circuits.
 In these configurations, changing the sample is often difficult.
 On the other hand, in MRI the wasted power is absorbed by the patient,
 posing limitations on 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 strength and duration.
 In modern MRI scanners, this is addressed by using quadrature coils 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GE2005,Glover1985"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In the most simple configuration, two perpendicular linearly-polarized
 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 coils are used.
 When transmitting, the sinusoidal current in the two coils has a relative
 phase shift of 90
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

, producing circular 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 polarization.
 Due to the large bore of MRI scanners, coils with geometries designed for
 imaging specific regions can be placed directly on the patient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Returning to the simple experiment, when 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 is turned on with an amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\gg T_{1}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\gg T_{2}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, relaxation effects may be temporarily ignored.
 If the total duration of the 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 pulse is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, then in the rotating frame
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{M}(\tau)=M_{0}\cos(\omega_{1}\tau)\hat{z}-M_{0}\sin(\omega_{1}\tau)\hat{y}.
\]

\end_inset

Let's consider the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}\tau=\tfrac{\pi}{2}$
\end_inset

, which is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

90-degree
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 pulse.
 Immediately following this pulse, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}(\tau)=-M_{0}\hat{y}$
\end_inset

, which is a 90
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 rotation from equilibrium.
 With components in the transverse plane, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{M}$
\end_inset

 precesses around 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The precessing magnetization induces a voltage in the coil, which is now
 used as a receiver.
 The voltage is converted into a complex signal, 
\begin_inset Formula $S(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Up to a constant, this is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
S(t) & =M_{transverse}(t)\exp\left(i(\omega_{0}-\omega_{ref})t\right)\label{eq:theory:complex-S(t)}\\
 & =\sqrt{M_{x}(t)^{2}+M_{y}(t)^{2}}\exp\left(i(\omega_{0}-\omega_{ref})t\right),\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{transverse}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the magnitude of the magnetization in the transverse (
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

) plane precessing at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{ref}$
\end_inset

 is a reference frequency corresponding to the center of the spectrum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking into account 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 relaxation, the signal after the 
\begin_inset Formula $90^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 pulse is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S(t)=M_{0}\exp\left(-t/T_{2}\right)\exp\left(i(\omega_{0}-\omega_{ref})t\right).\label{eq:theory:FID-lorentzian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $90^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 pulse gives the maximum signal intensity.
 If a 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 pulse was used instead, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{transverse}(0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S(0)$
\end_inset

 would both be reduced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The NMR signal acquired with a single pulse is called the Free Induction
 Decay (FID
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "FID"
description "Free Induction Decay"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 The Fourier transform of the FID gives the NMR spectrum, which in this
 case is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cavanagh2007"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
S(\omega) & =\mathcal{F}\left\{ S(t)u(t)e^{i\phi_{0}}\right\} \nonumber \\
 & =e^{i\phi_{0}}\left[\frac{T_{2}}{1+\left(\omega-\Delta\omega\right)^{2}T_{2}^{2}}-i\frac{\left(\omega-\Delta\omega\right)T_{2}^{2}}{1+\left(\omega-\Delta\omega\right)^{2}T_{2}^{2}}\right],\label{eq:theory:spectrum-lorentzian}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega=\omega_{0}-\omega_{ref}$
\end_inset

.
 The first and second terms in the brackets represent the absorption and
 dispersion parts of the Lorentzian lineshape.
 Two factors have been explicitly inserted prior to the Fourier transform:
 the zeroth-order phase factor, 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\phi_{0}},$
\end_inset

 and the unit step or Heaviside function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(t)$
\end_inset

, given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(t)=\begin{cases}
0 & t<0\\
1 & t>0.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

The first is necessary to complete the Fourier transform properly since
 
\begin_inset Formula $S(t<0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The second arises from the NMR receiver chain.
 In NMR, spectra are represented using the absorption lineshapes, so phase
 correcting 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\omega)$
\end_inset

 (multiplying by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-i\phi_{0}}$
\end_inset

 for a zeroth order correction) is necessary to isolate the pure absorption
 part.
 Exponential decay of the FID from the 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 time corresponds to a Lorentzian lineshape in the frequency domain.
 Evidently, the Bloch equations naturally lead to a Lorentzian lineshape.
\end_layout

